"""
MKT Context Commentary — Nehemiah chapters 9–10
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-nehemiah-9-10.py

Ch9:  ANE penitential prayer tradition — Mesopotamian šu-ila prayers as structural parallel (9:1)
      Ur of the Chaldeans — Neo-Babylonian Ur as major religious-commercial center (9:7)
      Sabbath origin — contrast with Mesopotamian šabattu (inauspicious 15th-day rest) (9:14)
      Sihon and Og — Transjordanian Iron Age I kingdoms; Heshbon archaeology (9:22)
      Persian tribute system — Achaemenid satrap taxation and Yehud's economic subordination (9:36-37)
      ANE suzerainty treaty forms — Hittite treaty structure as background for covenant document (9:38)
Ch10: Tirshatha — Aramaic loanword for Persian provincial governor (10:1)
      Third-shekel tax — reduced from Exod 30 half-shekel; Elephantine papyri temple financing (10:32)
      Wood offering — attested in Temple Scroll, Josephus, and Mishna Taanit 4:5 (10:34)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DATA = {
  "9": {
    "1": "<p>The penitential assembly of Nehemiah 9 belongs to the ANE tradition of communal lamentation and self-abasement before the deity. Mesopotamian penitential prayer literature — the <em>šu-ila</em> (hand-lifting) prayers and the <em>eršemma</em> (lament with harp) genre — employed fasting, sackcloth, and physical prostration as the standard posture of supplication. The 'Lament over the Destruction of Ur' and similar Sumerian city-laments employ the same structure of acknowledging divine judgment, confessing communal sin, and petitioning for restoration. The Nehemiah 9 prayer is distinctively Yahwistic (grounded in covenant history rather than astral deity-relations) but draws on the same widespread ANE penitential convention.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The separation of Israelites from foreigners at the assembly reflects the social-boundary dynamics of Persian-era Yehud. The returned exiles constituted a distinct sub-community within the broader population of the province, which included indigenous Judeans who had not been exiled, Samaritans, and various Gentile settlers. The Elephantine papyri (5th century BCE) document similar ethnic-religious community formation among the Jewish military colony in Egypt, where the Jewish community maintained distinct social boundaries despite living among Egyptians. The separation enacted in Neh 9:2 is the liturgical expression of the community identity politics that pervade the Ezra-Nehemiah reform.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The public Torah reading conducted for a quarter of the day (approximately three hours) reflects the emerging Second Temple liturgical institution of scriptural recitation. Deuteronomy 31:10-13 mandated a septennial public reading of the law at the Feast of Booths, and the Ezra-Nehemiah assembly (chs 8-9) represents one of the best-attested instances of this institution. The pattern of reading, interpretation (<em>mᵉpōrāš</em>, 8:8), and communal response became the structural template for the later synagogue liturgy, making Nehemiah's assembly one of the historically visible origins of the synagogue worship form.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The Levitical platform (<em>maʿălāh</em>, staircase/elevation) from which the prayer was led anticipates the <em>bema</em> (elevated reading platform) of later synagogue architecture. Ancient synagogues from the first-century BCE onward consistently feature an elevated reader's platform. The 3rd-2nd century BCE synagogues at Delos and Ostia, and the first-century CE Gamla synagogue in the Golan, all preserve the architectural principle of elevation for the leader of prayer and reading — a continuity from the Nehemiah-era temple-court assembly to the diaspora synagogue form.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Levitical blessing formula — calling the congregation to bless YHWH from everlasting to everlasting — is structurally parallel to the temple psalmody and the doxological framing of the Psalter (Ps 41:13; 72:18-19; 89:52; 106:48). The <em>beraḵāh</em> (blessing) formula in liturgical use functions as a performative declaration: the community does not merely describe YHWH as worthy of praise but enacts praise by articulating it corporately. This liturgical convention persists in the synagogue's <em>barekhu</em> (bless YHWH) call-and-response that opens formal prayer.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The creation confession of Neh 9:6 stands against the backdrop of Mesopotamian creation narratives — particularly the <em>Enuma Elish</em>, which describes creation as the outcome of divine conflict (Marduk defeating Tiamat) and assigns different domains to different deities. The Nehemiah prayer's monotheistic assertion — YHWH alone created all things and sustains them — is a deliberate counter-claim: there is one Creator of all domains, not a pantheon of domain-specific deities. The post-exilic context, where the Babylonian creation myth was the imperial narrative, makes this confession polemically charged.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Ur of the Chaldeans — the city from which Abraham was called (Gen 11:31; 15:7) — was one of the most important urban centers of the ancient Near East. The Ur III period (2112-2004 BCE) produced the famous Third Dynasty of Ur under kings Ur-Nammu and Shulgi, whose law codes (Ur-Nammu Law Code, c. 2100 BCE) predate the Mosaic code by centuries. The city was a major cult center for the moon-god Nanna/Sin. By the Neo-Babylonian period (when the exile occurred) Ur had been restored and remained a significant religious and commercial hub. The reference to Abraham's origin point in Ur grounds the covenant narrative in a specific, historically verifiable location.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The six-nation enumeration (Canaanites, Hittites, Amorites, Perizzites, Jebusites, Girgashites) reflects the standard ANE treaty-formula for land grants. Hittite suzerainty treaties from Hattusa (14th-13th centuries BCE) enumerate the territories granted to vassal kings with specific boundary descriptions and lists of peoples included or excluded from the grant. The similarity in form between Israelite covenant documents and Hittite suzerainty treaties has been extensively analyzed since George Mendenhall's 1954 study. The covenant's land-promise component uses the legal vocabulary of ANE imperial land grants.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The motif of YHWH seeing the affliction of his people and hearing their cry at the Reed Sea belongs to a wider ANE convention of deity-perception as the trigger of divine action. Egyptian texts describe Amun hearing the cry of his devotees; Mesopotamian petitionary prayers appeal to the deity's capacity to see distress. The distinctive element in the Exodus/Nehemiah formulation is the covenantal basis: YHWH responds not merely to distress but to the cry of covenant partners whose affliction is itself a violation of the imperial order YHWH will correct.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The Exodus plagues as signs and wonders operated in competition with the Egyptian court's own magical practitioners (Exod 7:11-12, 22; 8:7). Egyptian magical papyri document the role of court magicians (<em>ḥarṭummîm</em>, a Hebraized Egyptian loanword) in royal ceremonies and administrative functions. The plagues narrative presents YHWH's acts of power as superior to the entire apparatus of Egyptian state religion and magic — not merely natural catastrophes but targeted demonstrations of covenant sovereignty over the Egyptian gods (Exod 12:12).</p>",
    "11": "<p>The Reed Sea (Hebrew <em>yam sûph</em>) crossing has been located by scholars at various points along the isthmus between Egypt and Sinai — from the northern Serbonian Bog to the Bitter Lakes region to the Gulf of Suez. The 13th-century BCE Exodus context (under Ramesses II) corresponds geographically with the eastern delta region of the Nile. The Egyptian military context — chariots and horses as the elite strike force of the New Kingdom army — is well-documented in Egyptian military records (the Battle of Kadesh reliefs, Ramesses II chariot forces).</p>",
    "12": "<p>The pillar of cloud and fire as YHWH's guiding presence has partial analogues in Egyptian military practice: relief inscriptions depict Amun preceding the pharaoh's army as a column of divine presence. The Hittite king Mursilis II records a miraculous thundercloud that aided his army. These divine-sign traditions in military contexts provide the cultural background against which the Exodus pillar of cloud and fire would have been understood by the original audience — as a divine military escort exceeding any comparable protective presence in the ANE.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Mount Sinai's identification has been debated, with candidates including Jebel Musa in the southern Sinai (the traditional Byzantine site), Jebel Helal in northern Sinai, and Jebel al-Lawz in northwestern Arabia. The theophany pattern — divine descent in fire, smoke, earthquake (Exod 19:18) — corresponds to the volcanic/seismic characteristics of the northwestern Arabian volcanic field (<em>Harrat Khaybar</em>), which has influenced some scholars' identification of Sinai with that region. The law-giving context fits the ANE pattern of treaties delivered on sacred mountains (the Hittite mountain-sanctuary treaty ceremony).</p>",
    "14": "<p>The Israelite Sabbath is distinctive in the ANE. The Mesopotamian <em>šabattu</em> — attested in Akkadian calendars as the 15th day of the month (the full moon) — was an inauspicious day of rest for the king but not a weekly institution and not associated with creation theology. The seven-day week as a liturgical unit appears to have been distinctively Israelite in the ancient world, grounded in the creation narrative (Gen 2:1-3) and the Sinai covenant. The Sabbath-as-covenant-sign (Exod 31:12-17) made weekly Sabbath observance a visible boundary marker distinguishing Israel from surrounding cultures.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The manna of the wilderness is described as a small, white, wafer-like substance tasting like honey (Exod 16:14, 31). Natural candidates have been identified: the secretion of the tamarisk tree (<em>Tamarix mannifera</em>) produced by insects — a sweet, resinous exudate that appears on the ground in the Sinai in late spring and early summer. However, the quantity, timing, and Sabbath-doubling described in Exod 16 exceed any natural phenomenon, and the narrative frames it as supernatural provision. Water from the rock at Meribah (Exod 17:1-7; Num 20:2-13) may correspond to water released from porous limestone rock, but is similarly presented as miraculous.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The stiff-necked metaphor (<em>qāšāh ʿōreph</em>) derives from ancient agricultural practice. A draft ox that refuses to yield its neck to the yoke — that stiffens its neck against the driver's direction — is useless for plowing and dangerous to manage. The image was widely understood in an agrarian society where oxen were the primary power source for farming. ANE agricultural texts describe the training of draft animals and the cost of an uncontrollable ox. Applied to Israel, the metaphor vividly captures both the stubbornness and the practical futility of the rebellion.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The clause 'they appointed a leader to return to their slavery' (Num 14:4) echoes the Israelites' nostalgia for Egypt. Egypt in the mid-2nd millennium BCE was the most powerful state in the ancient world — the New Kingdom pharaohs controlled vast wealth, built monumental architecture, and commanded the most sophisticated army. The 'leeks, onions, and garlic' of Egypt (Num 11:5) were real agricultural products of the Nile delta's rich soil. The desire to return is not merely irrational: the security and food supply of Egypt were genuinely superior to the wilderness. The theological point is that covenant freedom is more valuable than imperial food security.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The golden calf episode (Exod 32) is illuminated by Canaanite and Phoenician religion. The bull was the standard iconographic representation of the storm-god Baal and of El the high god in the Ugaritic texts. Ugaritic literature (14th-13th centuries BCE) describes Baal as the son of the bull-god El and uses bovine imagery extensively for divine power. The golden calf may represent either the Egyptian bull-god Apis/Mneyis or — more likely given the Exodus/Sinai context — a Canaanite bull-deity adopted as a visible representation of YHWH, which is precisely what makes it idolatrous: attributing YHWH's Exodus power to a bull-icon.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The divine compassion (<em>raḥămîm</em>) that preserved Israel despite the golden calf apostasy represents a pattern documented across ANE religious literature: the tension between a deity's wrath at transgression and the deity's ultimate commitment to the worshipper community. Mesopotamian penitential psalms frequently invoke the deity's compassion as more powerful than his wrath: 'Your anger has consumed me — your mercy has not forsaken me' is the structural formula. The Nehemiah 9 prayer draws on this genre but grounds the appeal in covenant commitment (YHWH bound himself to Abraham) rather than mere divine sentiment.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The concept of a divine spirit given to instruct and guide a community has ANE parallels in the idea of a deity's <em>melammu</em> (divine radiance/aura) attending a king or community in battle and administrative matters. The distinctive Israelite contribution is the democratization of spirit-reception to the community level and the cognitive-pedagogical function (instructing rather than merely empowering). The Sinai/wilderness Spirit is the OT's first explicit statement of the Spirit as teacher — a function that becomes central in the prophetic (Isa 11:1-2) and then new covenant (Ezek 36:26-27) traditions.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The forty-year wilderness period is attested in the Pentateuchal tradition but its historical basis has been extensively debated. The Sinai has been traversed by Bedouin and military expeditions in historical periods without leaving large-scale archaeological traces — nomadic populations rarely do. The Egyptian administrative records (Papyrus Anastasi VI) document the Egyptian monitoring of Semitic peoples moving between Sinai and Egypt. The period corresponds roughly to a generation — the time required for the adult generation of Exod 12 to die and be replaced by the next generation (Num 14:29-35).</p>",
    "22": "<p>Sihon king of Heshbon is the first Transjordanian ruler Israel defeated (Num 21:21-31). Archaeological excavations at Tell Hesban (biblical Heshbon) in Jordan have revealed Iron Age I occupation layers consistent with the 13th-12th century BCE timeframe. Og king of Bashan ruled the volcanic plateau east of the Sea of Galilee — a region known for its basalt-built megalithic structures (dolmens) and Bronze/Iron Age cities. Og is associated with the giant Rephaim tradition (Deut 3:11) and his iron bed became legendary. The Transjordanian victories served as the military proof-of-concept for the western Canaan conquest.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The star-count metaphor for Israel's population — 'as the stars of heaven' — belongs to the Abrahamic promise tradition (Gen 15:5; 22:17). In the ancient world, star-counting was both a practical impossibility and the astronomer's constant challenge. Babylonian star catalogs (<em>Mul.Apin</em> series, c. 1200 BCE) attempted systematic stellar enumeration but acknowledged incompleteness. The metaphor of uncountable stars for an uncountable people was thus a maximally large number — what modern mathematics would approach with infinity. The fulfillment of this promise at the entry to Canaan is the prayer's narrative climax: what YHWH promised Abraham he accomplished.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The Conquest's Late Bronze Age context is one of the most debated historical questions in OT scholarship. The Late Bronze Age collapse (c. 1200-1150 BCE) saw the destruction of numerous Canaanite city-states (Hazor, Lachish, Megiddo) by unclear agents. Some destruction layers have been associated with Israelite entry; others with Egyptian campaigns (Ramesses III) or the Sea Peoples. The Merneptah Stele (c. 1208 BCE) is the earliest Egyptian reference to Israel as a people in Canaan — establishing that some form of 'Israel' was in Canaan by that date.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The inventory of Canaanite abundance in 9:25 — fortified cities, fat land, hewn cisterns, vineyards, olive orchards, fruit trees — reflects the actual agrarian economy of Iron Age I Canaan. Archaeological surveys of the Iron Age I highlands show a dramatic increase in small settlements precisely in the period associated with Israelite settlement (1200-1000 BCE), as new communities exploited the agricultural potential of the hill-country through terrace farming and rock-cut cisterns. The cisterns mentioned (Deut 6:11; Josh 24:13) are archaeologically attested throughout the central highlands.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The killing of the prophets (9:26) as a pattern of apostasy corresponds to what is known of the pre-exilic period's treatment of YHWH's messengers. Jeremiah's arrest and near-execution (Jer 38), Uriah's murder by Jehoiakim (Jer 26:20-23), and Elijah's persecution under Ahab and Jezebel (1 Kgs 19) document the violent suppression of prophetic witness. Jesus's use of this pattern in the Wicked Tenants parable (Mark 12:1-12) and his lament over Jerusalem (Luke 13:34) draws directly on the tradition that Nehemiah 9:26 encapsulates: the systematic destruction of the prophetic voice that called Israel back to covenant faithfulness.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The <em>môšîʿîm</em> (saviors) of the Judges era operated in the specific political context of Iron Age I tribalism — small, non-centralized communities living under the pressure of more organized neighbors (Philistines, Moabites, Midianites, Ammonites). The Book of Judges' archaeological correlate is the Iron Age I period of highland settlement (c. 1200-1000 BCE), when the village-based Israelite communities faced recurring raids and domination by the lowland powers. The judge-deliverers were charismatic military leaders who achieved local victories but could not create the institutional stability needed for long-term security — the limitation that drove the demand for a king.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The Judges cycle — covenant faithfulness, apostasy, oppression, cry, deliverance, rest, apostasy — is the historiographical framework of Judges 2:11-19 applied to the entire period. This cyclical interpretation of history is distinctive in the ANE: Mesopotamian histories tend toward linear narrative (king-lists, annals) rather than theological cycle. The Deuteronomic school's presentation of history as a series of covenant cycles is the distinctive Israelite contribution to ancient historiography — history as theology, not merely chronicle.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The role of the prophets in warning Israel (9:29-30) reflects the actual historical phenomenon of the 8th-7th century BCE prophetic movement — Amos, Hosea, Micah, Isaiah, Jeremiah, Ezekiel — who delivered covenant-warning messages to both northern and southern kingdoms before the respective destructions of Samaria (721 BCE) and Jerusalem (587 BCE). The Assyrian royal annals document the fall of Samaria (Sargon II's annals list 27,290 deportees) and Sennacherib's siege of Jerusalem — confirming the historical frame within which the prophets operated.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The divine patience over many years (9:30) corresponds to the historical span from the entry into Canaan (c. 1200 BCE) to the Babylonian exile (587 BCE) — approximately 600 years of covenant history with repeated cycles of judgment-delayed and judgment-executed. The Babylonian exile is well-documented in both OT sources and Babylonian records: the Babylonian Chronicle confirms Nebuchadnezzar's siege of Jerusalem (597 BCE) and the Lachish Letters document the final days of the Judean fortification system before the 587 destruction.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The preservation of a remnant through the Babylonian exile is historically documented by the Murashu Archive (5th century BCE Nippur, Babylon) which records business transactions by Jewish families with clearly Hebrew names — evidence of a functioning Jewish community in Babylonian exile maintaining identity and economic activity over several generations. The Jehoiachin Tablets from Babylon (discovered 1899-1900) record rations distributed to 'Yaukin king of the land of Yahudu' (Jehoiachin of Judah) and his sons — confirming the Babylonian captivity of the Davidic royal line.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The triple divine epithet 'great, mighty, awesome God' (<em>hāʾēl haggāḏôl haggibōr wᵉhannôrāʾ</em>) of Deut 10:17 became a standard liturgical formula in Second Temple Judaism. The Amidah (the central Jewish prayer of the synagogue, formalized in the early rabbinic period) opens with this exact triple epithet as part of the first blessing — demonstrating the continuity from Nehemiah's assembly to later synagogue worship. The formula represents the public theological declaration of YHWH's character as the basis for petitionary prayer.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The covenant-justice acknowledgment ('you are righteous in all that has come upon us') follows the standard ANE formula for accepting divine judgment without protest. Mesopotamian penitential literature employs a similar acknowledgment formula: the petitioner accepts that the deity's punishment was just before requesting mercy. The distinction in the Israelite form is the grounding in specific covenant violations rather than arbitrary divine anger: YHWH's righteousness is forensic-covenantal, not merely sovereign.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The comprehensive failure of the entire leadership chain — kings, princes, priests — corresponds to the historical record of the pre-exilic period. Archaeological evidence from the First Temple period includes numerous seal impressions and cult objects showing syncretistic religious practices among the official classes: horse figurines associated with sun-worship (cf. 2 Kgs 23:11), Asherah poles near the temple (2 Kgs 23:4-7), and the multiplied altar sites that archaeological surveys have documented throughout Judah.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The irony noted in 9:35 — apostasy in the midst of divine bounty — reflects the pattern documented in the 8th-7th century prosperity that accompanied economic growth under Uzziah and Jeroboam II. This period (c. 793-740 BCE) saw agricultural expansion, trade networks, and urban development documented in the Samaria Ostraca (administrative receipts recording oil and wine deliveries). Amos's critique of the wealthy elite (Amos 4:1; 6:1-7) targets precisely this context of prosperity-accompanied apostasy.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The Persian province of Yehud Medinata (the official Achaemenid administrative designation of the province) is documented in several sources: the Yehud coins (small bronze coins minted in the province during the 5th-4th centuries BCE), Yehud-stamped jar handles, and seals/bullae bearing the provincial name. The province was small — roughly 20 by 25 miles centered on Jerusalem — and its population estimated at 10,000-30,000. The tribute burden on this small, poor province is the economic backdrop for the complaint of 9:36-37.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Achaemenid tribute collection in the province of Yehud is documented in the Persepolis Fortification Tablets (509-494 BCE) and the Persepolis Treasury Tablets, which record rations distributed to workers from across the empire and the tribute flow toward the imperial center. The satrap of Transeuphrates (the administrative region including Yehud) was responsible for annual tribute delivery. Persian imperial taxation was heavy by ancient standards: Herodotus (3.89-97) records the tribute of each satrapy. Yehud's produce flowing to Persian coffers is exactly what the Persepolis records document.</p>",
    "38": "<p>The covenant document of Neh 9:38-10:39 belongs to the literary tradition of ANE suzerainty treaties. Hittite suzerainty treaty forms (14th-13th centuries BCE) include: preamble identifying the suzerain, historical prologue of past benefits, stipulations, document clause, witness list, and curse/blessing list. The Nehemiah covenant has similar elements: historical review (ch 9), stipulations (10:29-39), signatory list (10:2-27), and implied blessings/curses (the <em>ʾālāh û-šᵉḇûʿāh</em> of 10:29). The Second Temple community adapted the ancient treaty form to a voluntary covenant renewal rather than a political subjection treaty.</p>"
  },
  "10": {
    "1": "<p><span class='term'>tirshātāʾ</span> — the Governor — is an Aramaic loanword from Old Persian <em>tarsata</em> (the feared/honorable one), the standard Achaemenid designation for a provincial governor subordinate to the satrap. In the Persian administrative system, the satrap governed the large satrapy of Transeuphrates (Beyond the River), while the <em>tirshātāʾ</em> governed the sub-province (medinata). Nehemiah's official title in the Persian imperial hierarchy positions the covenant document as a legal instrument ratified by the recognized civil authority of Yehud — not merely a religious declaration but a legally recognized communal act within the Persian administrative framework.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The priestly family Seraiah heads the list of clerical signatories. Priestly lineages in the post-exilic community were verified against the genealogical records of the return (Ezra 2:36-39; Neh 7:39-42) — those who could not demonstrate priestly descent were excluded from the priesthood (Ezra 2:62). The careful naming of priestly family heads in the covenant document serves a legal function: it commits specific, named, verifiable households to the covenant obligations, particularly the intermarriage prohibition that directly affected priestly family choices.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The Pashhur family (Neh 10:3) appears across multiple Ezra-Nehemiah contexts: 832 members of this family returned from Babylon (Ezra 2:38; Neh 7:41), making it one of the larger priestly clans. Multiple Pashhur individuals appear in the narrative — one as a temple official who arrested Jeremiah (Jer 20:1-6), another as the family head of returnees. The continuity of priestly family names across the pre-exilic and post-exilic periods reflects the survival of priestly genealogical records through the exile.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Hattush son of Shecaniah (Neh 10:4) is identified in Ezra 8:2-3 as a descendant of David who returned with Ezra — a member of the Davidic royal line. His presence in the priestly signatory list may reflect either a broader classification or the social prestige that Davidic descent carried in the restoration community, even among those not formally priests. The presence of a Davidide among the covenant signatories signals the involvement of the entire community's elite structure.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Malluk and Harim priestly families (10:5) are attested in the intermarriage crisis list of Ezra 10: Harim's family had members who had married foreign women (Ezra 10:21, 31). Their presence as covenant signatories after the Ezra reforms represents the community's recommitment by the very families most directly implicated in the covenant violation — a narrative of repentance and renewed obligation.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Meremoth son of Uriah (10:6) served as the official weigher of the temple vessels brought by Ezra (Ezra 8:33) — one of the few individuals in Ezra-Nehemiah with a documented specific administrative function. The weighing of silver and gold vessels before deposit in the temple treasury reflects standard Achaemenid administrative accountability practices documented in the Persepolis Treasury Tablets, which record meticulous weight-and-commodity accounting.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The Abijah priestly division (10:7) is one of the 24 priestly divisions established by David for rotating temple service (1 Chr 24:7-18). The 24-division system was a pre-exilic administrative structure that the Second Temple period attempted to restore. John the Baptist's father Zechariah was of the division of Abijah (Luke 1:5) — demonstrating the continuity of the priestly division system from Nehemiah's covenant document through the Second Temple period to the NT era.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The completion of the priestly signatory list at 10:8 represents 21 priestly family heads — not the complete Aaronic priesthood but its recognized leadership in the restoration community. The number falls short of the 24 Davidic divisions, reflecting the attrition and incomplete records of the exile. The covenant document's priestly list is not a claim to completeness but a record of those families that were present, verified, and willing to sign.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The Levitical signatory list (10:9-13) begins with Joshua son of Azaniah. The Levites in the restoration community occupied a lower social status than the priests — a tension visible throughout Ezra-Nehemiah, where the Levites are fewer in number and have difficulty asserting their rights to tithes and temple service (Neh 13:10-13). The covenant document's explicit inclusion of Levitical family heads alongside priestly ones represents the institutional claim that both orders are equally bound by the covenant's terms.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Shebaniah (10:10) appears multiple times in the Nehemiah narrative, functioning as a Levite in the prayer-leading assembly (9:4-5). The recurrence of the same Levitical leaders across the liturgical and legal events of Nehemiah 8-10 reflects the small size of the Levitical community in the restoration: a tight circle of recognized leaders served across multiple functions in the community's institutional life.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The Levitical names in this list follow the same naming patterns as the priestly names — heavy use of Yahwistic theophoric compounds. The sociological practice of giving children names compounded with the divine name was a form of covenant identity maintenance in the exile and post-exile: each new generation born with a Yahweh-name embodied the communal claim to covenant relationship even in conditions of political subjection.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Hashabiah (10:12) is one of the most frequently recurring Levitical names in Chronicles-Ezra-Nehemiah. Multiple Hashab-yahs served in different capacities across the restoration period — a common enough name to make individual identification difficult but collectively indicating the Levitical lineage's ongoing commitment to temple service. The Chronicler's attention to Levitical genealogies (1 Chr 6:45; 9:14) reflects the institutional importance of documented service-lineage in the Second Temple priestly economy.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The close of the Levitical section (10:13) mirrors the priestly close (10:8) in explicitly labeling the group: these are the Levites. The parallel structural markers in the covenant document's layout reflect formal legal drafting conventions attested in ANE legal documents — the systematic enumeration and labeling of witness and signatory categories was a standard feature of ancient contract and covenant forms.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The lay leaders (10:14-27) represent the civil aristocracy of Persian-period Yehud — the family heads of the large returnee clans. In the Persian administrative system, local governance of sub-provincial communities was typically entrusted to traditional leadership structures (tribal elders, family heads) operating under the provincial governor's oversight. The lay leaders' signatures on the covenant document extend its legal force beyond the cultic personnel to the entire civic community.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The Bunni and Azgad families (10:15) are documented in the Ezra 2/Nehemiah 7 return census as major returnee groups. Azgad's 1,222 returnees (Ezra 2:12) made it one of the numerically significant lay families. Bunni appears in the return list (Neh 7:15) and among the Levites in the prayer assembly (9:4) — suggesting the name was shared across different social groups in the community.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Adonijah (10:16) is one of 5 leaders mentioned in Neh 10:16-17 with names shared by pre-exilic Israelite figures — a naming convention that deliberately links the restoration community to the pre-exilic covenant people. The practice of naming children after prominent biblical figures (kings, prophets, priests) was a form of cultural continuity through the disruption of exile — asserting that the same community, with the same identity, had returned from Babylon.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The Ater and Hezekiah families (10:17) reflect the mixed character of the returning community: Ater (bound/sealed) is a gate-keeper family (Ezra 2:42) while Hezekiah is a royal name carried by the reforming king of Judah (2 Kgs 18-20). The convergence of service families and aristocratic names in the lay signatory list reflects Yehud's democratic-covenant intent: all social strata from gatekeepers to those of royal name are equally bound by the same covenant obligations.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Hashum (10:18) is one of the families implicated in the Ezra intermarriage crisis (Ezra 10:33) — members of this family had married foreign women and are listed among those who put them away. The same family signing the covenant renewal document in Nehemiah demonstrates the processual character of covenant restoration: the Ezra crisis was not a one-time resolution but an ongoing community renegotiation of identity boundaries requiring renewed commitment.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Hariph (10:19) corresponds to the Jorah family of Ezra 2:18 (112 returnees) — the name variation may reflect scribal alternation or family-branch differentiation. Anathoth (10:19) as a family name invokes the association with Jeremiah's hometown — a priestly city in the territory of Benjamin that had been a center of prophetic activity in the pre-exilic period (Jer 1:1; 11:21-23). The community's naming of a family after Anathoth may preserve memory of the prophetic tradition connected with that location.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Meshullam (10:20) is the most frequent personal name in Ezra-Nehemiah, borne by individuals from priestly, Levitical, and lay groups alike. The name's frequency reflects its popularity in the early Second Temple period — possibly because its meaning (friend/ally of YHWH) expressed the restored community's self-understanding as YHWH's covenant partners. The multiplicity of Meshullams in the documents makes individual identification unreliable without additional genealogical information.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Meshezabel and Zadok (10:21) bear names with significant heritage: Meshezabel (God has delivered) is an exile-era name type expressing trust in divine rescue; Zadok carries the weight of the great high-priestly line of Israel (2 Sam 8:17; 1 Kgs 1:34). The Zadokite priesthood's legitimacy claim was contested in Second Temple Judaism — the Dead Sea Scrolls community (Qumran) defined itself as the true Sons of Zadok against the Jerusalem establishment. A lay Zadok among the covenant signatories represents the broad cultural reach of the name.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Pelaiah (10:22) — YHWH is marvelous/distinguishes — belongs to the category of post-exilic theophoric names that express wonder at divine action in the exile and return. The naming pattern of exile and restoration generations shows a marked increase in names expressing divine rescue and marvel (Pelaiah, Meshezabel, Elnathan) compared to pre-exilic names, reflecting the community's theological interpretation of its historical experience.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Hoshea (10:23) — salvation — is an ancient Israelite name borne by both the last king of Israel (2 Kgs 17:1) and the original name of Joshua/Yeshua (Num 13:8, 16). Its presence as a lay family name in the Nehemiah covenant document shows its continued use across the political disruption of the kingdom period. The name shares its root with the entire salvation-vocabulary of the OT — a name embodying the central covenant theme.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Hallohesh (10:24 — the whisperer) is an unusual name type; its bearer (or his father Hallohesh of Neh 3:12) participated in the wall-rebuilding. The presence of wall-building participants among the covenant signatories reflects the social overlap between the physical reconstruction project (Neh 1-7) and the spiritual-covenant reconstruction (Neh 8-10): the same community leadership was responsible for both forms of restoration.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Rehum (10:25) as a family name is shared with one of the official opponents of the Jerusalem rebuilding project (Ezra 4:8-9, 17, 23), though that Rehum was likely a Samaritan official. The coincidence of names highlights the complex social landscape of Persian-period Palestine, where names could be shared across ethnic and religious groups. The post-exilic community's name-records thus require careful attention to genealogical context rather than name alone for identification.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Ahijah (10:26 — YHWH is brother) carries the name of the Shilonite prophet who announced the division of the kingdom to Jeroboam (1 Kgs 11:29-40) and the prophetic tradition of the northern kingdom. The preservation of this prophetic name in the post-exilic Judean community reflects the pan-Israelite character of the restoration community: the returned exiles included those with northern-kingdom name traditions, not merely southern-kingdom Judahites.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The close of the lay signatory section (10:27) labels the group as the princes/leaders of the people. The three-tier structure of the covenant document — priests, Levites, lay leaders — mirrors the social organization of the Persian-period Yehud community and the concentric structure of the temple itself (priests in the inner courts, Levites in the outer courts, people in the temple precinct). The covenant document's structure encodes the social hierarchy of the restoration community in its literary form.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The extension of the covenant beyond the named signatories to 'all who separated themselves from the peoples of the lands' reflects the community's awareness that the covenant's binding force extends beyond the official signatories. Comparable extensions appear in ANE treaty documents where the treaty's obligations bind future generations and all members of the signatory party. The Elephantine papyri community similarly defined membership by separation from the surrounding Egyptian population — the social-boundary dynamic is not unique to Jerusalem but is attested across Jewish diaspora communities.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The <em>ʾālāh û-šᵉḇûʿāh</em> (curse and oath) formula of covenant sealing is well-documented in ANE legal tradition. Hittite treaties typically included elaborate curse-lists invoking divine punishment for treaty violation. The Israelite covenant form maintains this self-imprecatory element: the oath-taker invites divine judgment if the covenant is broken. In Babylonian and Assyrian treaties, the curse was enforced by the covenant's divine witnesses (the gods named in the preamble). In Israel's covenant, YHWH himself is both the covenant-maker and the guarantor of its sanctions.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The endogamy commitment (no intermarriage with the peoples of the land) reflects the social-boundary strategy of ethnically-defined minority communities under imperial rule. The Elephantine Jewish military colony in Egypt (5th century BCE) shows the challenge: Elephantine documents include both Jewish-Jewish marriages and marriages between Jewish men and Egyptian women, with the colony's adherence to Jewish law varying considerably. The Jerusalem community's written covenant commitment to endogamy represents a stricter stance than some diaspora communities maintained.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The Sabbath commerce prohibition became a major practical challenge documented in Nehemiah 13:15-22, where Nehemiah found Judeans treading wine-presses on the Sabbath and Tyrian merchants selling fish and goods in Jerusalem. This violation after the covenant pledge of 10:31 demonstrates the enforcement difficulty of the covenant obligations in a functioning commercial city. The Sabbath controversy continued through the Second Temple period and into the NT era, where rabbinic halakha developed extensive rulings on permitted and prohibited Sabbath activities.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The reduction of the annual temple tax from the half-shekel of Exod 30:13 to a third-shekel in Neh 10:32 likely reflects the economic conditions of the small, poor Persian-period Yehud community. The Elephantine papyri (specifically the Passover Letter, AP 21, and the financial records of the Elephantine temple) document Jewish diaspora communities contributing to temple funding — showing that the Jerusalem temple's financial support network extended to diaspora Jews as well as the local population.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The temple services funded by the annual contribution — showbread, regular offerings, Sabbath and festival sacrifices, sin offerings — represent the standard Second Temple cult calendar. The Mishnaic tractate <em>Sheqalim</em> (Shekels) documents the elaborate Second Temple system for collecting, storing, and disbursing the annual temple contribution — a development of the Nehemiah covenant pledge into a fully institutionalized temple-finance system.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The wood offering (<em>qurban hāʾēṣîm</em>) is not explicitly commanded in the Pentateuch but is extensively attested in Second Temple sources. The Temple Scroll (11QT col. 23-25) from Qumran describes a wood-offering festival spanning six two-day periods spread across the summer months, in which different family groups brought wood in rotation. Josephus (War 2.17.6) mentions a wood festival. The Mishnah (Taanit 4:5) preserves the calendar of nine wood-offering days with specific family assignments — a direct development of the lot-casting system of Neh 10:34.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The firstfruits covenant (10:35) corresponds to the agricultural cycle of Persian-period Yehud. The grain harvest ran from barley (spring) through wheat (early summer); the fruit harvest extended through summer and fall. The firstfruits festivals (Weeks/Shavuot for grain; Tabernacles/Sukkot for the final harvest) were the primary occasions for firstfruits presentation. Agricultural evidence from Persian-period Yehud includes storage facilities, wine/olive presses, and granary structures documented at sites like Ramat Rahel near Jerusalem.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The firstborn redemption system (10:36) required paying five shekels to redeem a firstborn son (Num 18:15-16) who otherwise theoretically belonged to YHWH. This practice is documented in rabbinic literature (Pidyon HaBen — Redemption of the Son) as a ceremony that has continued in traditional Jewish communities to the present day. The covenant pledge of Neh 10:36 represents the community's commitment to maintain this practice — one of the covenant obligations with the clearest continuous historical trajectory from Sinai to post-biblical Judaism.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The <em>ʾărîsāh</em> (dough offering) of 10:37 corresponds to the <em>hallah</em> of Num 15:20-21 — the first portion of each batch of dough dedicated to YHWH. This obligation became central to rabbinic household law: the separation of <em>challah</em> (hallah) from bread dough is one of the distinctively domestic Jewish practices, traditionally a women's obligation, that survived the destruction of the temple and the end of the sacrificial system. The covenant pledge of Neh 10:37 is the Second Temple-era reaffirmation of a practice that became central to diaspora Jewish identity.</p>",
    "38": "<p>The tithe system articulated in 10:38 — Levites receiving the tithe, priests receiving a tithe of the tithe — corresponds to the Num 18:21-28 structure. The Nehemiah 13:10-13 crisis (Levites had fled to work their fields because tithes were not being brought) demonstrates that this covenant pledge was difficult to maintain in practice. The Malachi 3:8-12 prophecy — 'will a man rob God? Yet you rob me in tithes and offerings' — belongs to the same Persian-period context of tithe non-observance that Nehemiah's reforms addressed.</p>",
    "39": "<p>The covenant climax — 'we will not neglect the house of our God' — establishes temple maintenance as the defining community obligation. This commitment is the institutional expression of the Levitical prayer's theological spine: as YHWH did not abandon (<em>ʿāzaḇ</em>) his people through all their apostasy, so the community commits not to abandon his house. The Second Temple period's subsequent history was shaped by this tension between the covenant pledge and the forces of neglect: Nehemiah himself had to enforce temple-support obligations repeatedly (13:10-13) against the tendency of the community to prioritize personal economic needs over temple funding.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'nehemiah')
    merge_comm(c, DATA)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'nehemiah', c)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in DATA.values())
    print(f'nehemiah mkt-context: wrote {count} verses across ch 9-10')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
